#!/usr/bin/env ssc
---
name: string-eq-locals
---

# string equality of two non-literal operands in an if condition

Regression for BUGS.md `v2-fbc-string-eq-optimistic`: the boolean fast-path
compiler (tryFBc) kept `==`/`!=` UNGUARDED while ordering ops required
provably-Long operands — tryFLC optimistically reads a Local as Long (StrV →
0L), so `if p == period` with two string locals compared 0 == 0 → always true
(busi incomeFor: the July fact leaked into the June query; five busi tests).

```scalascript
def sameMonth(p: String, period: String): Boolean =
  if p == period then true else false

def diffMonth(p: String, period: String): Boolean =
  if p != period then true else false

println(sameMonth("2026-07", "2026-06"))
println(sameMonth("2026-06", "2026-06"))
println(diffMonth("2026-07", "2026-06"))

case class Line(period: String, amount: Int)

def totalFor(xs: List[Line], period: String): Int =
  xs.foldLeft(0)((acc, l) => l match
    case Line(p, a) => if p == period then acc + a else acc)

val xs = List(Line("2026-06", 5000), Line("2026-06", 2000), Line("2026-07", 9000))
println(totalFor(xs, "2026-06"))
println(totalFor(xs, "2026-07"))
```
